THEORY
A stack is a linear data structure that follows the principle LIFO (Last In First Out).
In a stack, insertion and deletion of elements take place only at one end called TOP.
Basic Stack Operations
Push – Inserts an element into the stack.
Pop – Deletes the top element from the stack.
Display – Displays all elements of the stack from top to bottom.
Stack Conditions
Overflow occurs when we try to insert an element into a full stack.
Underflow occurs when we try to delete an element from an empty stack.
In this program, the stack is implemented using dynamic memory allocation with malloc().
ALGORITHM
Algorithm for PUSH operation
Start
Check if top == size - 1
If true, print Stack Overflow
Else
Increment top
Store element at stack[top]
Stop
Algorithm for POP operation
Start
Check if top == -1
If true, print Stack is empty
Else
Print element at stack[top]
Decrement top
Stop
Algorithm for DISPLAY operation
Start
Check if top == -1
If true, print Stack is empty
Else
Print elements from top to 0
Stop
PROGRAM
Copy code
C
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int size = 5;
int top = -1;
int *stack;

void push(int x) {
    if (top == size - 1) {
        printf("Stack Overflow\n");
    } else {
        top++;
        stack[top] = x;
    }
}

void pop() {
    if (top == -1) {
        printf("Stack is empty\n");
    } else {
        printf("Popped element: %d\n", stack[top]);
        top--;
    }
}

void display() {
    if (top == -1) {
        printf("Stack is empty\n");
    } else {
        printf("Stack elements:\n");
        for (int i = top; i >= 0; i--) {
            printf("%d ", stack[i]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
}

int main() {
    stack = (int *)malloc(size * sizeof(int));

    push(10);
    push(20);
    display();

    pop();
    push(30);
    display();

    free(stack);
    return 0;
}
OUTPUT
Copy code

Stack elements:
20 10
Popped element: 20
Stack elements:
30 10
